<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,303,330,356]" box="[189,303,330,356]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,330,356]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,330,356]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[188,1399,376,508]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Species can be identified as members of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Saussure &amp; Zehntner" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[761,913,376,402]" class="Diplopoda" family="Arthrosphaeridae" genus="Zoosphaerium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sphaerotheriida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piligerum">
<emphasis box="[761,913,376,402]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Z. piligerum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group based on morphological characters of the posterior telopods (
<bibRefCitation author="Wesener T. &amp; Wagele J. W." box="[612,909,412,438]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="5 - 82" refId="ref28537" refString="Wesener T. &amp; Wagele J. W. 2008. The giant pill-millipedes of Madagascar: revision of the genus Zoosphaerium (Myriapoda, Diplopoda, Sphaerotheriida). Zoosystema 30 (1): 5 - 82." type="journal article" year="2008">Wesener &amp; Wägele 2008</bibRefCitation>
), which are slender and greatly elongated. The species-group now contains four described species distributed in the eastern rainforests at higher elevations (Wesener 2009).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,930,547,574]" box="[189,930,547,574]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,930,547,574]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,930,547,574]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Key to species of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="de Saussure &amp; Zehntner" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[450,751,547,574]" class="Diplopoda" family="Arthrosphaeridae" genus="Zoosphaerium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sphaerotheriida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piligerum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[450,751,547,574]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Zoosphaerium piligerum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="key">
<key pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<keyStep pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,594,1244]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<keyLead pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
1. Antenna with four apical cones. Endotergum without cuticular impressions. Third podomere of anterior telopods lateral of cavity without sclerotized teeth. Body length &lt;
<quantity box="[1188,1278,629,656]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="20.0">20 mm</quantity>
. Movable finger of posterior telopods&gt;4.5 times as long as wide ......... 
<taxonomicName authority="Wesener, 2009" authorityName="Wesener" authorityYear="2009" box="[987,1399,664,691]" class="Diplopoda" family="Arthrosphaeridae" genus="Zoosphaerium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sphaerotheriida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micropiligerum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[987,1211,664,691]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Z. micropiligerum</emphasis>
Wesener, 2009
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,594,1244]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<keyLead pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
– Antenna with&gt;10 apical cones. Endotergum with a single row of circular cuticular impressions. Third podomere of anterior telopods with at least two large, sclerotized teeth. Body length of mature females&gt; 
<quantity box="[446,534,770,797]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="35.0">35 mm</quantity>
. Movable finger of posterior telopods ≤ 3.5 times as long as wide.......2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,594,1244]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<keyLead pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
2. Anal shield bell-shaped. Posterior telopod fixed finger strongly curved, ca 25% shorter than movable finger. Operculum of vulva protruding above coxal margin. Endotergum with two rows of marginal bristles, slightly extending beyond tergite margin ......................................................... ..................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="(de Saussure &amp; Zehntner, 1897)" baseAuthorityName="de Saussure &amp; Zehntner" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[858,1398,941,968]" class="Diplopoda" family="Arthrosphaeridae" genus="Zoosphaerium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sphaerotheriida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piligerum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[858,1009,941,968]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Z. piligerum</emphasis>
(de 
<bibRefCitation author="Saussure H. de &amp; Zehntner L." box="[1064,1390,941,967]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" pagination="1 - 12" refId="ref27664" refString="Saussure H. de &amp; Zehntner L. 1897. Atlas de l'histoire naturelle des Myriapodes. Histoire physique, naturelle et politique de Madagascar 27 (53): 1 - 12." type="journal article" year="1897">Saussure &amp; Zehntner, 1897</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,594,1244]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<keyLead pageId="33" pageNumber="34">– Anal shield well rounded. Posterior telopod fixed finger slightly curved, only slightly shorter than movable finger. Operculum of vulva not reaching coxal margin. Endotergum with a single row of marginal bristles, not reaching tergite margin.....................................................................3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,594,1244]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<keyLead pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
3. Tergites matte, covered with short setae, dark brown. Third podomere of anterior telopods laterally with 3 or 4 crenulated teeth. Legs with 10–12 ventral spines ................ 
<taxonomicName authority="Wesener &amp; Sagorny, 2021" authorityName="Wesener &amp; Sagorny" authorityYear="2021" box="[1081,1298,1147,1174]" class="Diplopoda" family="Arthrosphaeridae" genus="Zoosphaerium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sphaerotheriida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinopiligerum" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1081,1298,1147,1174]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Z. spinopiligerum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1307,1399,1148,1174]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="33.[189,1399,594,1244]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<keyLead pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
– Tergites glossy, black. Third podomere of anterior telopods laterally with 1 or 2 crenulated teeth. Legs with 8 or 9 ventral spines ..................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Wesener, 2009" authorityName="Wesener" authorityYear="2009" box="[974,1399,1217,1244]" class="Diplopoda" family="Arthrosphaeridae" genus="Zoosphaerium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sphaerotheriida" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudopiligerum">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[974,1212,1217,1244]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Z. pseudopiligerum</emphasis>
Wesener, 2009
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
</subSubSection>
